{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868892/1930090501/0446.xml":{"full_text":"The Milwaukee Leader\nAction Would Be Better\nThan Talk\nAgain some of the administration officials at Washington are\nmaking rosy reports regarding a prospective upturn in industrial\naffairs and a return of \u201cprosperity.\u201d\nIt may be true that the bottom has been reached and that an\nupturn is due \u2014we hope so\u2014but predictions from administration\nofficials do not impress us. There was once a boy who cried \u201cWolf!\u201d\nso often that nobody believed him. Yet, if the administration of\nficials keep on predicting an upturn, there must come a time when\nthey will be correct. Doubtless they will then say, \u201cThere, didn\u2019t\nwe tell you so?\u201d and the times when they were mistaken will be\nforgotten.\nIn the meanwhile, iLwould be more to the point if the adminis\ntration would call congress in special session to pass an unemploy\nment insurance bill and to enact other legislation for the relief and\nprevention of unemployment.\nWHERE STATE POLICE\nFORCE WAS ABANDONED\nThe sudden drive on the part of Gover\nnor Kohler for a force of state snoopers,\napparently in an attempt to line up the pro\nhibition vote for the governor in the present\ncampaign, has resulted in a flood of pub\nlicity, favorable to the establishment of a\nstate police force in Wisconsin\u2019s Dry-papers\n\u2014the dryest of which is The Milwaukee\nJournal.\nThe average citizen will be told that\nstate police forces are a tremendous suc\ncess.\nTherefore The Leader asks each voter\nto remember the following facts:\nColorado had a state police force and\nabandoned it.\nArizona had a state police force and\nabandoned it.\nIdaho had a state police force and aban\ndoned it.\nNew Mexico had a state police force and\nabandoned it.\nTexas had a state police force and aban\ndoned it.\nThe press agents for prohibition who\nwrite editorials for The Milwaukee Jour\nnal and who seem to be dancing in their\neagerness to erect a state snoopers system\nin the Badger state should notice that all\nof the states that have abandoned state po\nlice forces are dry states\u2014so that the state\npolice departments are not a success even\nin prohibition territory.\nOf course the so-called \u201cstate sheriff\u2019s\noffice\u201d in South Dakota is principally an\nagent for the enforcement of the state pro\nhibition law. But our state prohibition law\nhas been repealed in the Duncan referen\ndum, April, 1929\u2014Although The Milwau\nkee Journal fought bitterly on the dry side\nof that campaign as it has in every other\nwet and dry fight.\nTh\nen of course The Wisconsin Agricul\nturist, Wisconsin Dry-paper, Feb. 9, 1929,\nin an editorial quotes Senator Markham\n(Kohler Republican of Dodge county) as\nbelieving* \u201cthat there\u2019is no reason why a\nstate police force should not handle pro\nhibition law violations.\u201d\nAnd farther along in the same editorial,\nThe Wisconsin Agriculturist says \u201cThe\nstate police force of Michigan has taken\nover prohibition enforcement so that the\npolice is meeting with praise on all sides.\u201d\nNaturally we may expect the drys to\nfight enthusiastically for the state snooper\nidea.\nWAR IS NOT HEROIC\nAll Quiet on the Western Front is\nagain running in Milwaukee, this time at\nAlhambra. Those who have not seen it\nshould do so if possible.\nA writer in The Milwaukee Journal\ntries to blunt the keen moral of this play\nand make out that it is heroic for youth to\nbe ready and willing to go to war.\nIt is exactly the opposite. There is no\ngenuine heroism in war. There is no virtue\nin blatant nationalism.\nIn individual conduct, it is now pretty\nwell recognized that fighting and the use\nof force generally is unmanly and disgrace\nful unless force is used strictly in self-de\nfense.\nThe same applies to the use of collective\nforce, termed war. It is unmanly and dis\ngraceful unless used strictly in self-de\nfense. And when we say \u201cself-defense,\u201d we\nmean real self-defense, not the spurious\npretense of self-defense in which nearly all\nof the belligerent nations, including our\nown, indulged during the World war. If\nour country were actually invaded by an\nother country, it would be necessary to\nrepel the invaders. No other sort of war is\njustifiable.\nTrue heroism does not lie in fighting.\nTrue heroism is confined to peaceful pur\nsuits and abstention from war\u2014and moral\nheroism is far and away above physical\nheroism. In the World war, the conscien\ntious objectors, military and civil, were the\nreal heroes.\nEDITORS'\nIvy Poisoning\nThe immediate remedy for itch\ning skin is very hot water. It\nmust be extremely hot. Warm wa\nter will not do any good at all\nbut hot water will relieve all\nkinds of skin irritation. By the\nproper use of hot water itching\nand burning and smarting, all\nsorts of skin irritation, paricular\nly Itching, may be removed im\nmediately. The pain of a bee sting\nor eczema or ivy poisoning or itch\ning from any cause whatever\nmay be removed at once by a\nvery hot application.\nThe procedure is to take a towel\njust as it comes from the laundry.\nDraw the hottest water you can\npossibly get into the wash basin\nand immerse the center of the\ntowel. Keep the ends of it dry so\nthat you can take hold of it, but\nput the center down into the hot\nwater. Then as vou draw it over\nthe edge of the washbowl put a\ntumbler on it and press hard and\nas you pull it through that will\npress the water out and leave it\nsmooth. If you wring it out it\nleaves ridges. You must have a\nsmooth surface, so it is quite im\nportant that you press the water\nout. 1\nAnother way to heat your towel\nis to use a hot iron. An electric\niron is an excellent thing. The\nother day I got a mosquito bite\non my nose. It was really very\ndistressing. I took a towel and\nprepared it as I told you. I\ndoubled it over, applied the elec\ntric iron, and then took hold of\nthe dry ends and touched the\ntowel to the end of my nose in\nlittle quick taps.\nIt was so hot it would have\nblistered if held on for a few sec\nonds. I had to pull it away quick\nly, barely touching the surface of\nthe skin. After 10 touches the\nsmarting ceased. In a half hour\nthe swelling disappeared' and it\nwas entirely cured.\nIn ivy poison or eczema or any\nkind of skin itching, nettle rash\nor urticaria, you can always get\nrelief by an application of this\nsort. A lady came into my office\na year ago last summer with her\neyes swollen shut. She had a\npiece of ice in each hand. She\nrubbed the ice on her eyes and she\nwould get just a little glimpse.\nShe had been ill a week. She suf\nfered from a terrible attack of\nptomaine poisoning. However, she\nhad gotten over it with the ex\nception of her eyes, which were\nterribly swollen and for which she\ncould find no relief. She was suf\nfering terribly. I said to her, \u201cjust\ncome here to this washbowl and\nyou will be relieved in four or,\nfive minutes.\u201d Well, she could\nhardly believe it, but I made this\nsimple application just as I have\ntold you, first on one eye and then\non the other and in less than two\nminutes the swelling had disap\npearing, the itching was complete\nly gone and the lady was very\nhappy. In ten minutes she \u2018left\nthe office with her eyes wide open,\nentirely relieved.\nOne day as I was going to the\nhospital to do some surgery, I\nfound a lady standing in the hos\npital door and she had both arms\nuncovered and stretched out in a\nmost pitiful way. Her arms looked\nlike beefsteak. They were in a\nterrible state of inflammation.\nShe had had ivy poisoning and\nshe said. \u201cI have been suffering\ntwo weeks with this ivy poison\ning. I have not slept for three\nnights. It is getting steadily worse.\nI have had everything possible\ndone for it. I have not had any\nsleep at all for three days and\nnights.\u201d She looked really beside\nherself, she was in such distress.\nI said, \u201cCome in and you will\nbe relieved in four or five min\nutes.\u201d\nShe said, \u201cThat is impossible;\nthat would l>e a miracle.\u201d\nI said, \u201cAll right, we will have\na miracle then. Come right along.\u201d\nI got some hot water and applied\nit in just the manner I have ex\nplained to you and in less than\nfive minutes she was almost en\ntirely relieved. I advised her to\nrepeat this application two or\nthree times a day. In three days\nshe was entirely well of her ivy\npoisoning.\nThis is such a simple remedy\nyou will probably forget it and\nyou will try all kinds of liniments\nand go through a whole lot of\nmisery without much relief and\nby and by. perhaps, you will re\nmember what T have told you\nabout this and you will get relief\nin five or ten minutes. Do not\nforget to tell your neighbors\nabout it.\u2014Dr. ohn Harvey Kel\nlogg.\nGreat Fighter\nProud Parent (who served in\nA. E. F.) \u2014And that which I\nhave just told you. son, is the\nstory of my experience in the\nWorld war.\nHis son\u2014But. papa, what did\nthey need the rest of the army\nfor?\nTHE LABOR PARTY\u2019S FIRST\nPARLIAMENTARY YEAR\nForty-eight government bills received the royal\nassent. The chief of those were the finance bill,\nthe coal mines act, the unemployment insurance act\nand the widows\u2019, orphans\u2019 and old age pensions\nact. Vigorous and sustained Tory opposition to\nthe government\u2019s efforts had to be overcome at ev\nery stage as is shown by the fact that on those\nfour measures alone there were 281 divisions. The\ntime occupied in these divisions is roughly equiva\nlent to seven normal daily sittings of the house of\ncommons I\nIn addition to this mass of legislation tlere\nhave been also the naval agreement with America\nami Japan, The Hague reparations settlement, the\nevacuation of the Rhineland, the ratification of the\noptional clause, the resumption of diplomatic rela\ntions with Russia, a new treaty of alliance vith\nIraq, and the near settlement of the Egyptian piob\nlem.\nDuring the present parliamentary recess the\ngovernment will be occupied with the assembly of\nthe league of nations, then the coming imperial\nconference, and after that the Indian round tade\nconference.\nI he\nin the more domestic sphere the government is\nbusily engaged on its agricultural policy, the brosd\noutlines of which were announced by Mr. Snov\nden on the day on which the first session came o\nan end. Proposals will be submitted for makiig\nland more freely available for small cultivators aid\naffording them adequate security of tenure, I\nscheme will be undertaken whereby a contributioi\nmay be made to the mitigation of unemployment b'\nthe creation of a special class of allotments and b;\nmodel gardens and poultry holdings up to five acre,\nfor suitable unemployed workers. An agricultura\nland utilization corporation will be established t<\nconduct huge scale farming and a chain of demon\nstration farms. The question of the condition of\ncereal farmers in different parts of the empire will\nbe considered by the imperial conference, and after\nwards the government will undertake whatevr\npracticable steps can be devised to put cereal grow\ning in this country on an economic foundation. A\nagricultural marketing bill is being introducd\nforthwith, which will confer certain powers a\nlarge-scale commodity organizations, initiated k\nthe producers, for the marketing of home product,\nand to protect such organizations from the disru\ntive action of minorities. Long and short-ten\nfinancial loans will be available for these commoe\nity farming boards. As for the worker, wage;\nhousing and rent conditions will receive special ai\ntention.\nIt is clear from these brief indications of futun\nwork that the second year of the Labor governmen\nis not likely to be any less exacting than that whicl\nwas so recently concluded.\u2014Labor and Socialis\nInternational.\nNEW NATIONAL EDITION\nOF MILWAUKEE LEADER\nThe Milwaukee Leader has just commerced\nthe publication of a national edition called Che\nAmerican Leader.\nTh Am'\nie aeriean Leader is part of the progam\nof expansion to make The Milwaukee Leader one\nof the most influential publications in Ameria in\nthe interests of labor and its political actior\nThe field for The American Leader is tie en\ntire American continent. The plan is to male it a\ndaily record of the activities of the labqr, Social\nist and liberal movements of the nation.\nThe new edition is designed primarily for read\ners outside the state. One of its chief fettures\nwill be a monthly index in which all the miterial\npublished in the paper will be listed for rea<y ref\nerence.\u2014Labor and Socialist International (iurich,\nSwitzerland.)\nFOR EXAMINATIONS\nThe fact that those states that go abou: the ex\namination and licensing of drivers in an irtelligent\nmanner have the smallest death rates on the roads\nought to convince Michigan that it is tine for it\n\u2014the very home of the motor car industry\u2014to get\ninto line. Conferences and meetings and speeches\nand editorials are not enough. Better laws will not\nprevent all killings, because the foolhardy and the\nrash, like the poor, are always with us. But bet\nter laws, properly enforced, will eliminjte many\nunfit drivers from the ranks of the mota-ists and\nwill remove unsafe vehicles from public highways.\nAction, rather than reports and surveys,' s what is\nneeded.\u2014-Adrian (Mich.) Telegram.\nTHE RIGHT ANSWER\nThe Hungarian Society for Foreign Politics and\nthe league of nations, whose chairman is Count\nApponyi, formerly a minister in Hungary, recently\napproached the International Transput Workers\u2019\nFederation (I. T. F.) with a request for informa\ntion on the activity of the I. T. F. an? its organ\nizations in Hungary, together with the names and\naddresses of its leading people living h this coun\ntry.\nThe secretariat of the I. T. F. informed the so\nciety that in view of Hungary\u2019s attitude on the\nprovisions of the peace treaty regarding the right\nof association, it refuses to give th* desired in\nformation.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nPublished Id Milwaukee. Wls.. every afternoon ex\ncept Sundav. EDITORIAL AND PUBLICATION\nOFFICES: 628-32 Juneau Avenue at Sixth Street\nTelephone; Marqnette 7500.\nE. J. COSTELLO. Editor.\nAssociate Editor John M Work: Managing Editor.\nLeo Wolfsohn: City Editor. Frank Haggerty; Sports\nEditor Ben Smith: Advertising Manager Elmer A\nKrahn.\nEntered as second class matter August 25, 1920. at the\npostoffice at Milwaukee. Wia\u201e under the act of March 3. 1879\nSUBSCRIPTION RaTES\u2014Mail editions tn United\nStates: Three months. $1.60: six months. ^3: one\nvear. $6 To foreign countries: Three months. $3:\nsix months $6: one vear sl2\nThe home edition is delivered by carriers tn Mil\nwaukee and county for 15 cents a week or 65 cents a\nmonth: elsewhere by carrier. 18 cents a week or 80\ncents a month.\nADVERTISING subject to publisher\u2019s acceptance.\nRates on application FOREIGN ADVERTISING\nREPRESENTATIVES: Frallck. Bates Alward. Inc.\nNew York: 270 Madison Avenue. Room 1301. Chicago:\n605 North Michigan Avenue. San Francisco and Los\nAngeUa.\nSECTION\nDifficult Lessons\ny --v v 'I SI z\ni'\nI' \u2019ll\nI\u25a0 I\n1 It ULi\nH r*\u2014>\nP U \u2014-W\ni I iff\nf fi -A A f r\ng\nit Bi\nJJlgEra --Z/az S MWjw..\n-M 91 L\nI J\nk L II 1 -fl zPd j\nz >A\" n V/Z><7s\naBWMHra z L\n-at zHM a^.- 1 5\nst A Zk' I I\nr 'j ,v>UAa\"S \u25a0r- 4kfU .n I s u\u00bb\ny sWw oHcX was one ha^\ni 4 ff'W ww A\n>'-b'.' /..AZA\nThousands of children of as\nsorted ages have gone back to\nschool, and harrassed mothers\nheave sighs of relief. In our quiet\ncity and in this peaceful genera\ntion mothers can be reasonably\ncertain that when Jane and John\nny are sent off to school in the\nmorning they will return in the\nafternoon with their full quota of\nears, noses and teeth.\nBut in my boyhood in Chicago\nthere was always the danger of\nbeing brought home in pieces by\na thoughtful policeman. Going to\nschool, in those days, was like\nmarching into the jungle to the\nkindly embrace of head-hunters\nand gorillas. No wonder mother\noften wept when she ushered us\nthrough the door, school-bound.\nIt is distressing to say goodby\nto a couple of kids completely\nfurnished with toes, fingers and\ntonsils, and to have them brought\nhome again in a paper bag.\n\nChicago in my childhood, under\nthe benign rule of Carter Harri\nson, was beginning to enter the\ngang rule age which reached such\nglorious heights with the inven\ntion of the machine gun and the\ncoining of prohibition. The gangs\nStone Fences\nObserving tourists are responsi\nble for the report that stone\nfences are disappearing from the\nfarms of New England and New\nYork state. If this news is con\nfirmed on any large scale, it is\nsomething to \u201cview with alarm\u201d\nas well as regret. Can it really\nbe that thesS solid walls which\nhave fringed the country high\nways, served as/line fences\u201d be\ntween farms, and cut broad mead\nows up in orderly squares like a\ncheckerboard, are actually vanish\ning from the landscape? We are\ninformed that some of them are\nbeing sacrificed for base and top\ndressing of hard surface highways.\nOthers are being removed because\nthey are unsightly, or take up too\nmuch room.\nIt is true that old-fashioned\nstone fences usually were three or\nfour feet thick, but meadow and\npasture land must be soaring in\nprice if the space occupied by\nthese venerable walls is consid\nered wasted. And who ever heard\nof stone fences being \u201cunsightly?\u201d\nIn fact, they have been one of the\nmost picturesque features of New\nEngland farms for a century or\nmore. Has the artistic sense van\nished among modern farmers? A\nstraight, level, trim stone wall\nwas always a thing of beauty, and\none that straggled a little, was\nth o r oughly weather-beaten, or\nwas tumbled down a bit here and\nthere, was even more so.\nAnd think of the labor involved\nin buiKing\u2014and removing\u2014them.\nThe ones on the farm of our boy\nhood were the product of years\nof \u201cslack spells,\u201d showery days\nwhen hay could not be drawn to\nthe barn, and, we sadly recall, of\ninnumerable days when we would\nhave preferred to do most any\nthing else instead of \u201cpick stone.\u201d\nIt seemed to us that retreating\nglaciers had left most of their de\nposit of stones on our farm! But\nit was a joy to see a field cleared\nof stones, and whether it was a\nmeadow or a cornfield it made the\nplowing and mowing a much less\nstrenuous job.\nIf these stone walls disappear,\nwe wonder what the wild grapes\nand \u201cchokecherries\u201d will do. The\nbest ones always grew along the\nold wall. Chipmunks will have to\nfind a new place to scamper. And\nin the autumn when butternuts\nare ripe on the old tree down in\nthe pasture, where will farmer\nboys go to crack the nuts. Noth\ning in the world was quite so well\nsuited to this purpose as a shady\nspot on a stone wall. If all the\nother stone walls disappear, we\nhope the one under which our\nboyhood brook ran will be spared,\nwith its cool moss-covered stones\nand the wild mint that grew be\nside them Christian Science\nMonitor.\nMAKING LIGHT Of THE TIMES\nin that generation were, of course,\nhampered by the mechanical\nbackwardness of the time, and\nyet they achieved no little distinc\ntion with ordinary brass-knuckles,\nguns, sandbags and bricks. Scar\nface Al Capone had not yet at\ntained the heights to which his\nmerits entitled him. But there\nwere others who, in their modest\nway, contributed not a little to\nthe glamour of the Harrison over\nlordship.\nA successful gangster is the\nproduct of a long and arduous\nschool training. And our neigh\nborhood, in a tough district on\nNorth Clarke st., was one of the\nmore notable crime kindergartens\nof our delightful city. Here lit\ntle boys, some not yet in their\nteens, learned the quiet art of\nleaping from an alley to slug a\nfoeman with a sockful of plaster,\nand the simple delight of acquir\ning bananas from a push-cart\npeddler by means of a shrewdly\naimed brick.\nThese innocent children were\ndivided into rival gangs who\nprowled the byways under terri\nfying banners. One gang called\nitself the Robey Street Rene\ngades, another The Sluggers, and\nihe most notable of the frater\nnities was a company called The\nClarke Street Apaches. This was\nled by a powerful, over-stuffed\nItalian youth of the name of\nLuigi the Lamplighter. That was\nthe age of street-corner gas\nlamps, lit each night by a boy\narmed with ladder and taper,\nand Luigi had the ward \u201cgraft\u201d\non lamplighting and dealt out his\nfavors and punishments with\nmuch spitting and swagger.\nOf Luigi I stood in particular\nfear. In my nightmares to this\nday his swarthy face, thrust for\nward sharply from a pair of pow\nerful shoulders, fills me with\nthe same panic that seized me\nwhen I heard the yell of him or\nhis gang: \u201cYa-hoo ya\nhooooo Patchee\nPatchee!\u201d How often that dread\nshout of the Clarke Street\nApaches sent me cowering behind\nan ash barrel in some littered\nalley, or sent me leaping wildly\nover back fences, across roofs\nand lots to escape the devil at\nmy heels, and come home with\nmy clothing in shreds and the\nsweat of exhaustion on my face.\nSometimes they caught me. Of\nthese occasions I dislike to think,\nfor my back still tingles with the\nrecollection of their favorite pas\ntime running the captive\nthrough a double line of inquisi\ntors armed with paddles and sec\ntions of garden hose.\n\nThe gangs, luckily, for the most\npart scorned the trifling pleas\nures that come from twisting a\nschoolboy\u2019s ears and tearing\nWONDERS ot the WORLD\nTHE STORY OF IRON.\nThe rocks of the earth are\nman\u2019s treasure house. In them\nare stored most of our most pre\ncious possessions from salt to\ndiamonds, from chalk to radium.\nIndeed, there is every reason to\nbelieve that there are more valu\nables than we dream of hidden\naway in this rocky storehouse but\nwe do not yet know how to re\nlease them nor what their use to\nus may be.\nThe precious stones \u2014diamonds,\nrubies, emeralds and sapphires as\nwell as many others not quite so\nvaluable, and the gold and silver\nand radium and platinum, are\nonly an infinitesimal part of the\nearth\u2019s crust.\nIron is much more abundant\nthan all of these put together.\nAnd it has a very strange history.\nAt first iron, like all of these\nother things, was a part of the\nhot stuff which hardened into the\nrocks of the earth. But the water\nof lakes and streams dissolved\nmuch of it out and kept it as a\nliquid part of itself. Then along\ncame the bacteria, little germ-like\nplants who did us the immeasur-\nBY E. L. MEYEB\nBY GLUYAS WILLIAMS\noff his shirt to keep as a souve\nnir. They loved the more robust\ndelights of fighting rival gangs\nin a body, when they could em\nploy the mannish accoutrements\nof billies, rusty revolvers and\nhomemade brass knuckles.\nThe favorite tourney fieJ4 was\na weedy vacant lot some two\nblocks square which was known\nas Logermann\u2019s Prairie. Peaceful\nchildren coming home from school\nwere careful to avoid crossing\nthat prairie after dusk, for they\nwere likely to become the unwill\ning participators in a general\nbutchery. The policemen in our\ndistrict were fat and generally\nasthmatic, and as a rule, before\nthe \u2019\u201cpaddy wagon\u201d had rolled up\nto the field with reserves from\nthe precinct police station, the\nforms of half a dozen young com\nbatants were lying among the\nthistles and burdocks, laid flat\nby bullets or a barrage of brok\nen glass bottles. I am sure that\nmany a full-grown Chicago\ngangster today mastered his trade\nduring these jousts on Loger\nmann\u2019s Prairie. And I sometimes\nthink that if I had profited from\nobservation, and joined the\nApaches or the Sluggers and\nstudied the gangster art industri\nously, I might have attained\u2019 the\ndistinction of Searface Al and\nwould be hobnobbing today with\npolice captains, rum runners and\nall manner of great and success\nfi|l men. It just goes to show\nyou what happens when you\ndon't listen to the knock of op\nportunity.\n\nA couple of years ago, on a\nvisit to Chicago, I sought out the\nold neighborhood. But I searched\nin vain for Logermann\u2019s Prairie.\nI located the boundaries of that\nplace easily enough, but oh, the\ndifference. Where the still, white\nforms of unconscious Apaches\nhad once faced the moon, there\nnow were erected row after row\nof job-lot three-story apartment\nhouses, all cast out of the same\nmould. I listened in vain for the\n\u201cYa-hoo! Patchee!\u201d but heard\nonly a woman beating a rug, and\na child squawling, and a listless\nnewsboy calling extras.\nI asked the listless newsboy\nwhether he belonged to the\nApaches or the Sluggers, and he\nsaid no, he was a member of the\nY. M. C. A. and the District\nJunior Republican league. I gave\nthe extra youth a dime, thank\nful for the end of the reign of\nLuigi the Lamplighter, and yet\nas I went away I had a distinct\nfeeling of dejection because I had\nnot met the horrible Luigi in\nstead of the model boy. It is,\nafter all, more amusing to watch\na gorilla in a zoo gnashing his\nyellow teeth than to observe a\nhousecat lapping milk.\nable service of changing the liquid\niron into a solid once more, and\nputting it back into the water.\n559\nHow these little plants worked\nthis magic change, we can only\nguess. Somehow, they took the\niron into themselves, and their\nFriday, September 5, 1930 z\nSplinters\nAll work and no play makes\njack for the nerve specialists.\nEarly to bed and early to rise\nmeans an alarm clock must do the\nwork of flies.\nIf man is the only snob, why\ndo trout bite so darned well for\na president?\nThere is no lack of honesty in\nAmerica. The problem is to get\nit distributed evenly.\nIt isn't hard to manage a hus\nband. Haven\u2019t you noticed how\ncheerfully Willie labors when\nmother brags on his muscle?\n\n.0\u2014 Mr r>\nNo wonder infants are free of\ntemptation. So many of them are\nbald.\nThat liquor found on New York\ngarbage scows might not have\naroused suspicion if it hadn\u2019t\nbeen in bottles.\nThere\u2019s a way to stop bull fight\ning. No Spaniard could stick a\nsword in the breed that furnished\nour luncheon steak.\nWhen you study the districts\nthat have the homicide rates,\nyou can\u2019t help thinking that na\nture knows best.\nAll farmers are up against it,\nand those that have begun to keep\nbees will get stung in the end.\nThe better hotels now have run\nning ice water, but it\u2019s still neces\nsary to \u2019phone down for ginger\nale.\nI\nAnother interesting game con\nsists in trying to recognize your\ncar by the shape of the fenders\nafter it has been parked an hour.\nWe all eat much the same food.\nThe chief difference is that the\ntable scraps of the poor reappear\nas hash instead of a salad.\nStribling\u2019s ne w 1 y-discovered\npunch would have seemed even\nmore remarkable if it had\nknocked Scott perpendicular.\nThe chief danger in offering\n$lO for a used car now is that\nthe dealer won\u2019t have anything\nbut small change.\nBlessed are the poor. They\ncan cultivate new acquaintances\nwithout being asked to sign notes.\nAmericanism: Expressing a\ngreat scorn for politicians who\nare hypocrites; hiding your faults\nfrom Junior in order to set him a\ngood example.\nYou don\u2019t realize how much\nsuffering the human countenance\ncan reveal until you see a fat bald\nman teased by a cabaret singer.\nYou can tell when you have\nreached the wild and woolly west.\nNobody in a dinner jacket sticks\na gun against your ribs.\nFame comes slowly to artists.\nOnly time can fade a picture so\nthat nobody can tell how it\nlooked when new.\nIn a few more years, no veteran\nneed answer the question: \u201cWhat\ndid you do in the great war,\ndad?\u201d He can just point at the\nbookcase.\nMr. Edison\u2019s questionnaires af\nford good mental exercise. And\nif they come too seldom you can\ntry getting home at 3 a. m.\nIn the old days the man who\ncarried his liquor without show\ning it needed a hard head instead\nof flappy pants.\nOne way to meet all of your\ncreditors is to sit in your car\nwhile the gas station man obeys\norders to fill \u2019er up.\nCorrect this sentence: \u201cI didn\u2019t\ncare in my courtship days,\u201d said\nhe, \u201cbut now that I\u2019m married I\nshave and take a bath every day.\u201d\nbodies, tiny as they were, chem\nically changed it into a solid and\nput it back into the water, layer\nupon layer until there were ridges\nand walls of it, ready for us ic\nmine, hundreds of thousands of\nyears later.\nMost of these iron mountains\nbuilt by the tiny plants ages and\nages ago are far under the sur\nface of the earth, but sometimes\nthere are outcroppings of the\nmetal.\nThe bacteria were particularly\nbusy near Lake Superior, where\nfor many years our shovels and\npicks have dug into the earth for\nthe treasure they deposited. An\nother huge vein extends from New\nYork to Birmingham, but for the\nmost part this iron is deep down\nbelow the surface.\nWe do not know exactly when\nthe iron which now builds our\ncities and makes our machinery\nwas first changed into a solid by\nthe bacteria, but mountains have\nbeen tumbled up since and buried\nmuch of it far below them.\nNext\u2014From Felucca to Sham\nrock V.\n(Copyright, 198\u00b0. by Republic Syndi\ncate, Inc.)","height":"28431","width":"21072"}}
